:::summary
The Crusades were a series of religious wars sanctioned by the papacy, primarily aimed at recovering the Holy Land from Muslim control. Launched in 1095 by Pope Urban II, they spanned nearly two centuries and involved Christians from across Europe. Complex in their motivations — religious devotion, political ambition, economic opportunity, and genuine piety mixed with brutal violence — the Crusades profoundly shaped medieval Europe, the Middle East, and the relationship between Christianity and Islam that continues to this day.
:::

